node.text:
This exercise is included in my “Emotions 101” online course! The course is only available for purchase until May 2nd - so I highly recommend getting on this list. Click the link in my bio to get your spot!

Some disclaimers about these exercises:
- If you have a trauma history, experience flashbacks, have trouble with emotional regulation, experience suicidal ideation, or any other distressing symptoms, I highly recommend and suggest you practice these exercises with a trauma-informed, licensed therapist first.
- If at any point these exercises cause you to feel so overwhelmed or uncomfortable that you cannot continue, stop. Take note of any symptoms of distress: eyes fluttering, becoming hypervigilant, rapid or unsettled body movements, feeling overly uncomfortable, rapid heartbeat, overheating, or any other common signs of emotional flooding you experience.
- Before getting started, you may want to have some grounding items around you. Start in a comfortable space with things that help you remain calm. This may be a blanket, a photo, etc.
- Remember, you are the expert on your body and your experience. If something doesn’t work for you - that’s ok.
- Instead of judging or questioning yourself, try to stay with what is happening in your body. You can ask yourself questions like:
How am I noticing these feelings?
What is my experience like right now?
What is my body experiencing?
What am I wondering about?
What would help me feel safe right now?
- If you are really struggling with being still and reflecting on your internal experience, it may be best to practice mindfulness in other ways - like while eating, taking a shower, etc. to practice.

@drcarolineleaf and @sitwithwhit discuss Dr. Leaf’s new book! We chat about the desire to find a “quick fix,” finding what works for you, and skilled mind management.

You can get @drcarolineleaf ‘s new book anywhere where books are sold! I hear it’s selling out quick - so get your copy soon! If you’re reading it, would love to hear your favorite parts.

node.title: Cleaning Up Your Mental Mess with @drcarolineleaf

node.text:
Back in my office @thecollaborativemiami today and thought I’d record my first IGTV video ever! Tackling the questions: Why do people stay in bad relationships?

Let’s talk about why it’s so hard to “just leave.”

Disclaimer: If you are being abused, emotionally or physically, you are not at fault. If the abuse is still going on and the other person has not made a deliberate effort to seek help and/or change their behavior, the relationship is not safe. These other signs are not possible until the abuse has stopped and the abuser takes responsibility for their actions and their role. I’m going to include some available resources in the caption of this video.

Leaving a toxic relationship can also be dangerous. I know most of us don’t think it would happen to us, but there are millions of reported cases of domestic violence a year in the US. Remember that your safety is most important. Here are some resources I recommend:
* Find a therapist in your area that specializes in abusive relationships.
* Support groups:
 Adult Children of Alcoholics
 ALANON
 Trauma Survivor Groups
 Domestic Violence Support Groups
* National Domestic Violence Hotline: 800-799-SAFE
* Books
 Gaslighting - Stephanie Sarkis
 The Gaslight Effect - Robin Stern
 Adult Children of Emotionally Immature Parents - Lindsey Gibson
* Domesticshelters.org has a lot of resources and book suggestions

PS. it’s EMAIL DAY! Make sure to vote for the topic in my stories and swipe up to get on my email list.

node.title: Why People Stay In Bad Relationships

node.text:
What marriage advice would you give your younger self?

Thank you for your submissions! Feel free to leave more advice below 👇🏼

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit what marriage advice would you give your younger self?'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? Take and give space, grow and let them grow. Do new things together. *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? It's not going to be easy. But worth it. Keep going. The grass is green where it's watered. *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? Learn what healthy relationships and boundaries are first, what had mirrored for me was not. First, find out who you are then find someone who can compliment that and whom you can grow with together and apart. *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? You can't read minds and either can your partner. Talk but also listen *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? Don't marry potential. *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? Do what works for you both not what everyone else does *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? Don't marry someone thinking they will change, they won't *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? If they want you to change most things about you, they are NOT the one! Believe the red flags! *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft on July 14, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'what marriage advice would you give your younger self? You don't have to EVER get married, even though is expected of you by your family. *sourced from your community responses* @sitwithwhit'.

Photo by whitney goodman lmft in Little Havana. May be an image of text that says 'Whitney Goodman, LMFT @sitwithwhit Questions that may be hard to answer when someone is dysregulated or very overwhelmed: -what do you need? -what's wrong? help? -what happened? -why are you acting like this? -are you ok? -what is going on? -how can'.

node.text:
When someone is having a panic attack, their nervous system is in overdrive, they’re overwhelmed, etc….it can be very difficult to form a cohesive thought.

I know these questions seem helpful/easy, but in moments of crisis they may not actually be that simple to answer.

So what do you do instead?

Try to focus on creating safety. Sit there. Breathe. Be present. Listen. Follow their lead when they’re ready.

Discuss what someone needs when things are calm. Be prepared for this rather than being reactive. Make a list, have a toolbox. It helps so much.

node.text:
There was a time in my life where I thought an exciting relationship meant breaking up every two weeks, only to get back together and fight about the same shit on repeat.

There’s a rush that you feel in this type of relationship. It’s addictive. The cycle of losing and getting someone back keeps you hooked.

If you’ve been in a relationship like this, you know what I’m talking about. The hope of things getting better, saving the person, or fixing it keeps you trapped in the cycle. You just know this time it’s going to “work.”

But do you even really want it to work? A lot of you may find yourself feeling restless or “bored” when a relationship is stable. You may even create fights to spice things up again…

It’s a never ending cycle.

You can have safe and exciting relationships. It’s all about transforming what you view as “exciting.” The rush that you get in the break-up + get back together cycle is probably something you learned. It feels safe because it’s what you saw and experienced. You value that rollercoaster of emotions.

This is your definition of love and passion.

The best relationships are exciting because they are safe. I would argue that to experience true love and adventure, you have to have safety. The foundation is non-negotiable.

You want your relationship to be the safe place you can always return to. It’s a delicate dance that each couple will need to navigate. You have to figure out what combination feels right for you.

How have you made your relationship both safe and exciting?

node.text:
Yesterday I asked you all if it’s hard to answer the question, “what’s wrong?” when you’re overwhelmed or emotional. So many of you said yes and asked for this list of other options.

Adults are expected to regulate themselves.

We grow up and suddenly are responsible for our thoughts, feelings, and actions.

Self regulation is essential to living a full, balanced life. But, it’s not the only way we regulate our physical and emotional reactions to things.

Our ability to self regulate or manage our own emotions really depends on how our parents co-regulated with us as children and how safe we feel in our relationships as adults.

Co-regulation is how we help each other  manage distress. When we ask the question, “what’s wrong?” We’re ultimately trying to get information so we can fix it. This isn’t a bad thing! Unfortunately, when someone is really overwhelmed, it might be very hard to answer that.

A nervous system that is consistently co-regulated will eventually learn to regulate itself.

Co-regulation helps manage distress and allows connection, safety, and improved self regulation skills to be developed.

Next time you are with someone who is distressed, think about how you can make this a safer space for both of you. The goal is to create a space where they can share their experience without you having to force it out.

This is extremely personal and will vary person to person. As always, do what is right for you and them. **ask for consent before touching anyone and do not use touch if you’re not certain it’s appropriate, allowed, or helpful for this person and this relationship**

node.text:
As requested in the comments today. Here are a few ways you can start the convo when someone upsets you. Of course for these to work the other person needs to be willing to hear you out and have a conversation.

A couple of notes:
- make this your own and to fit your language
- sometimes “it made me feel” fits because it encourages accountability. Other times, “I felt” fits better. People and actions can lead to feelings, you’re not always causing it on your own or choosing.
- you statements can breed defensiveness and sometimes they’re unavoidable. When someone yells, it’s appropriate to say “when you yelled, I felt.” You could say, “yelling usually causes me to feel X,” but it might not have the same impact.
- you don’t have to start the conversation with these phrases. It may be best to ask them to talk or share what you’d like to talk about first.
- tone, body language, etc. will alter how these phrases land.
- just because someone doesn’t respond well, doesn’t mean you’re not doing this right. This will only work with someone willing to receive it.
- It’s best to do this when you’re both calm and regulated. Don’t be afraid to take breaks, ask questions, etc.
- you will need to alter these depending on the relationship.

Can we talk about it when you're ready?" "Can you help me understand where this conversation went wrong? I'm really trying to work on this." "I'm sorry for how reacted. can see how X was hurtful. I'm going to work on that:" @SITWITHWHIT'.
